M|Prin|tx|Before removing or changing something, first understand why it exists.
M|Prin|tx|> "Don't ever take a fence down until you know the reason it was put up." -- G.K. Chesterton
M|Deci|tx|Use this md during **Decomposition** (Steps 1-2) to surface hidden assumptions abt existing systems.
M|Veri|When|
M|Veri|tx|1. What problem did the existing thing originally solve?
M|Veri|tx|2. Are those original constraints still active?
M|Veri|tx|3. What implicit dependencies exist that the proposer may not see?
M|Veri|tx|4. Has anyone consulted the people who built it?
M|Red |tx|\| Signal \| Risk \|
M|Red |tx|\|--------\|------\|
M|Red |tx|\| "This is legacy, remove it" \| Original constraints unknown \|
M|Red |tx|\| "Nobody knows why this exists" \| Institutional knowledge gap \|
M|Red |tx|\| "We don't need this anymore" \| Implicit dependencies unexamined \|
M|Red |tx|\| "Let's start fresh" \| Second sy Effect risk \|
M|Fail|it|Reintroducing bugs that were previously fixed
M|Fail|it|Breaking implicit dependencies downstream
M|Fail|it|Losing institutional knowledge permanently
M|Fail|it|Triggering cascading failures in systems coupled to the removed cp
